{{Infobox Wrestling event |name=Super Extreme Wrestling War |image= |promotion=[[Frontier Martial-Arts Wrestling]] |date={{dts|1997|12|19}}&ndash;{{dts|1997|12|22}}<ref name="purolove">{{cite web|url=http://www.purolove.com/misc/fmw/results/97extremewar.php|title=Frontier Martial-Arts Wrestling - "SUPER EXTREME WRESTLING WAR 1997"|publisher=Puro Love|accessdate=2017-11-27|language=German}}</ref> |venue= |city= |attendance=15,300 (combined)<ref name="purolove"/> |liveevent= |event= |lastevent2= |nextevent2= }} '''Super Extreme Wrestling War''' was a series of [[professional wrestling]] events produced by [[Frontier Martial-Arts Wrestling]] (FMW) in 1997. These events marked the first time that FMW began a partnership with American counterpart [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]] (ECW) and a working relationship began between the two companies as ECW wrestlers competed at these events and it marked the beginning of interpromotional matches and events between ECW and FMW. These events would create a huge impact in FMW's [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Angle|storylines]] as they concluded with the breakup of [[ZEN (professional wrestling)|ZEN]] when [[Mr. Gannosuke]], [[Kouhiro Kanemura|Yukihiro Kanemura]] and [[Hido (wrestler)|Hido]] attacked their leader [[Atsushi Onita]] out of jealousy after [[Hayabusa (wrestler)|Hayabusa]] pinned Onita in a [[WarGames match]]. They merged with [[Fuyuki-Gun]] to form [[Team No Respect]], which would dominate FMW until 2000.
