}}'''The Glasgow Gaiety Theatre''' was a cine-theatre in [[Anderston Cross]], [[Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]. Originally known as the Victoria Music Hall, then the Tivoli Variety Theatre, and co-founded by a grandson of [[James Baylis]] of the [[Theatre Royal, Glasgow]] it opened in 1899 presenting [[Musicals]], [[variety shows]] and [[pantomimes]]. When it was rebuilt in 1904 it changed to operate as a cine-variety under the name of Gaiety Theatre, becoming a full cinema in 1935. The Beatles appeared there in 1963. The cinema closed in 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freewebs.com/glasgow-empire/theglasgowempirestory.htm|publisher=University of Glasgow|title=Glasgow Gaeity theatre|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arthurlloyd.co.uk/Glasgow/Tivoli.htm|title=The Glasgow Gaiety|accessdate=10 July 2009}}</ref> It is not to be confused with the Gaiety Theatre, Sauchiehall Street, which became the Empire Theatre.

